(iStock) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Providence - The founder and executive director of a Rhode Island refugee organization says he's planning to start a newspaper in the west African country he fled a decade ago.Omar Bah says he plans to launch a private, independent newspaper in Gambia that will be an alternative to government-controlled media there.Bah is a former Gambian journalist. He says he fled the country in 2006 after being beaten, kicked and tortured while trying to cover a secret trial. He arrived in Rhode Island in 2007. He directs the Providence-based Refugee Dream Centre.Bah announced his plans in a First Amendment blog run by Roger Williams University.He says he's motivated by a government crisis involving Gambia's longtime ruler, President Yahya Jammeh, who lost a December 1 election but hasn't accepted defeat.24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.